nation covers all continents and language families to uncover not only how languages die, but also how they can be revitalized—for example in the remarkable case of Hebrew. In a striking metaphor, Hagège likens languages to bonfires of social behavior that leave behind sparks even after they die; from these sparks languages can be rekindled and made to live again.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Feb 2021) 0aLanguage obsolescence. 0aLanguage revival. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aGladding, Jody.40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300155792423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300155792.jpg  aGBV-deGruyter-alles